---
/**
 * rest-api/0004 · Figure 2 — "good vs bad URIs" (nouns + method-is-the-verb on
 * the left, verbs-in-path / RPC-in-disguise on the right).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from docs/rest-api/lessons/0004-resource-modeling-and-uri-design.html
 * (figure + svg + figcaption). Lives as an .astro component because MDX's JSX
 * parser is unreliable with raw inline SVG using kebab-case attributes.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 196"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Good versus bad URIs: noun-based paths with the method as the verb versus verbs encoded in the path"
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <rect
                x="8"
                y="14"
                width="306"
                height="172"
                rx="10"
                fill="#eef5ee"
                stroke="#2f5d3a"
                stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
            <text
                x="161"
                y="36"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="12"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#2f5d3a">✓ NOUNS — method is the verb</text
            >
            <g font-family="ui-monospace,SFMono-Regular,Menlo,monospace" font-size="11.5">
                <text x="26" y="64" fill="#2f5d3a" font-weight="700">GET</text><text
                    x="76"
                    y="64"
                    fill="#111110">/orders/42</text
                >
                <text x="26" y="88" fill="#2f5d3a" font-weight="700">POST</text><text
                    x="76"
                    y="88"
                    fill="#111110">/orders</text
                >
                <text x="26" y="112" fill="#2f5d3a" font-weight="700">PATCH</text><text
                    x="76"
                    y="112"
                    fill="#111110">/orders/42</text
                >
                <text x="26" y="136" fill="#2f5d3a" font-weight="700">DELETE</text><text
                    x="76"
                    y="136"
                    fill="#111110">/orders/42</text
                >
            </g>
            <text x="161" y="166" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#244a2e"
                >uniform · cacheable · idempotency &amp; status apply</text
            >

            <rect
                x="326"
                y="14"
                width="306"
                height="172"
                rx="10"
                fill="#f7ecea"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
            <text
                x="479"
                y="36"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="12"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#9a2417">✗ VERBS-IN-PATH — RPC in disguise</text
            >
            <g font-family="ui-monospace,SFMono-Regular,Menlo,monospace" font-size="11.5">
                <text x="344" y="64" fill="#9a2417" font-weight="700">POST</text><text
                    x="394"
                    y="64"
                    fill="#7a2218">/getOrder</text
                >
                <text x="344" y="88" fill="#9a2417" font-weight="700">POST</text><text
                    x="394"
                    y="88"
                    fill="#7a2218">/createOrder</text
                >
                <text x="344" y="112" fill="#9a2417" font-weight="700">POST</text><text
                    x="394"
                    y="112"
                    fill="#7a2218">/cancelOrder</text
                >
                <text x="344" y="136" fill="#9a2417" font-weight="700">POST</text><text
                    x="394"
                    y="136"
                    fill="#7a2218">/orders/42/delete</text
                >
            </g>
            <text x="479" y="166" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#7a2218"
                >every endpoint a bespoke procedure · HTTP machinery off</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        Smuggle a verb into the path and caching, idempotency, and status semantics stop applying.
        Naming the resource correctly is the load-bearing decision.
    </figcaption>
</figure>
